"Rybski D., Bunde A.","On the detection of trends in long-term correlated records",2009,"Physica A: Statistical Mechanics and its Applications","388","8",,"1687","1695",,,10.1016/j.physa.2008.12.026,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-59449100309&partnerID=40&md5=6d17f320e1276cc5f16ded5dcccd0b23","Institut für Theoretische Physik III, Justus-Liebig-Universität Giessen, 35392 Giessen, Germany; Levich Institute, Physics Department, City College of New York, New York, NY 10031, United States","Rybski, D., Institut für Theoretische Physik III, Justus-Liebig-Universität Giessen, 35392 Giessen, Germany, Levich Institute, Physics Department, City College of New York, New York, NY 10031, United States; Bunde, A., Institut für Theoretische Physik III, Justus-Liebig-Universität Giessen, 35392 Giessen, Germany","We use the Detrended Fluctuation Analysis (DFA) to quantify underlying trends in long-term correlated records. Our approach is based on the fact that different orders of DFA are affected differently by trends. For a given instrumental record of length N, we compare the fluctuation exponent α0 of DFA0 where trends are not being eliminated, with the fluctuation exponent α2 of DFA2 where possible linear trends in the instrumental record are being eliminated. From this we deduce numerically the probability density p (A) that in the considered long-term correlated record, a linear trend with a slope between A and A + d A occurs. Without loss of generality we focus on Gaussian distributed data. As an example, we apply our analysis to several long temperature records (Melbourne, Oxford, Prague, Pusan, Uppsala, and Vienna), where we discuss the trends within the last 90 years, which may originate from both, urban and global warming. © 2008 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.","Climate; Detection; Detrended fluctuation analysis; Long-term correlations; Temperature; Trends","Global warming; Climate; Detection; Detrended fluctuation analysis; Long-term correlations; Temperature; Trends; Probability density function",,,,,,"Hurst, H.E., Long-term storage capacity of reservoirs (1951) Transactions of the American Society of Civil Engineers, 116 (2447), pp. 770-808; Mandelbrot, B.B., Wallis, J.R., Noah, Joseph, and operational hydrology (1968) Water Resources Research, 4 (5), pp. 909-918; Mandelbrot, B.B., Wallis, J.R., Some long-run properties of geophysical records (1969) Water Resources Research, 5 (2), pp. 321-340; Koscielny-Bunde, E., Bunde, A., Havlin, S., Goldreich, Y., Analysis of daily temperature fluctuations (1996) Physica A, 231 (4), pp. 393-396; Pelletier, J.D., Turcotte, D.L., Long-range persistence in climatological and hydrological time series: Analysis, modeling and application to drought hazard assessment (1997) Journal of Hydrology, 203 (1-4), pp. 198-208; Koscielny-Bunde, E., Bunde, A., Havlin, S., Roman, H.E., Goldreich, Y., Schellnhuber, H.-J., Indication of a universal persistence law governing atmospheric variability (1998) Physical Review Letters, 81 (3), pp. 729-732; Talkner, P., Weber, R.O., Power spectrum and detrended fluctuation analysis: Application to daily temperatures (2000) Physical Review E, 62 (1), pp. 150-160; Weber, R.O., Talkner, P., Spectra and correlations of climate data from days to decades (2001) Journal of Geophysical Research-Atmospheres, 106 (D17), pp. 20131-20144; Eichner, J.F., Koscielny-Bunde, E., Bunde, A., Havlin, S., Schellnhuber, H.-J., Power-law persistence and trends in the atmosphere: A detailed study of long temperature records (2003) Physical Review E, 68 (4), p. 046133; Monetti, R.A., Havlin, S., Bunde, A., Long-term persistence in the sea surface temperature fluctuations (2003) Physica A, 320, pp. 581-589; Király, A., Bartos, I., Jánosi, I.M., Correlation properties of daily temperature anomalies over land (2006) Tellus, 58 A (5), pp. 593-600; Rybski, D., Bunde, A., von Storch, H., Long-term memory in 1000 years simulated temperature records (2008) Journal of Geophysic